{"number":58287,"title":"[BUG] TaskCanceledException are reported when using Azure Monitor and HttpClient in .NET 10","body":"### Library name and version

Azure.Monitor.OpenTelemetry.AspNetCore 1.4.0

### Describe the bug

In a Blazor project we use HttpClient to call various services.
Those are cancelled if user tries to do the same thing twice, this leads to reported TaskCanceledException in Azure Application Insights. This only happens in .NET 10, not in .NET 8.
If other kind of async tasks are Cancelled, those are not reported.

Or is there any way to filter out TaskCanceledException when reported from the HttpClient?
Or have I missed some setting?
Or is this an issue with the HttpClient?

For us, this leads to a substantial amount of reported Exceptions that should be ignored, also leads to Azure Monitor reporting lots of false Alert Exception Anomalies...

### Expected behavior

Since a normal TaskCanceledException is not reported, we did not expect TaskCanceledException from the HttpClient to be reported.
Also in .NET 8, it is not reported, as expected.

### Actual behavior

This is reported (sorry about the Swedish text in the stack trace):
System.Threading.Tasks.TaskCanceledException: The operation was canceled.
 ---&gt; System.IO.IOException: Unable to read data from the transport connection: I/O-åtgärden har avbrutits därför att en tråd har avslutats eller för att ett program har begärt det..
 ---&gt; System.Net.Sockets.SocketException (995): I/O-åtgärden har avbrutits därför att en tråd har avslutats eller för att ett program har begärt det.
   --- End of inner exception stack trace ---
   at System.Net.Sockets.Socket.AwaitableSocketAsyncEventArgs.ThrowException(SocketError error, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at System.Net.Sockets.Socket.AwaitableSocketAsyncEventArgs.System.Threading.Tasks.Sources.IValueTaskSource.GetResult(Int16 token)
   at System.Net.Http.HttpConnection.InitialFillAsync(Boolean async)
   at System.Net.Http.HttpConnection.SendAsync(HttpRequestMessage request, Boolean async, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   --- End of inner exception stack trace ---
   at System.Net.Http.HttpConnection.SendAsync(HttpRequestMessage request, Boolean async, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at System.Net.Http.HttpConnectionPool.SendWithVersionDetectionAndRetryAsync(HttpRequestMessage request, Boolean async, Boolean doRequestAuth, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at System.Net.Http.Metrics.MetricsHandler.SendAsyncWithMetrics(HttpRequestMessage request, Boolean async, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
   at System.Net.Http.DiagnosticsHandler.SendAsyncCore(HttpRequestMessage request, Boolean async, CancellationToken cancellationToken)

### Reproduction Steps

Create new Blazor Server .NET 10 project with sample pages.
Add reference to: Azure.Monitor.OpenTelemetry.AspNetCore 1.4.0

In Program.cs (replace [MyKey]:
`builder.Services.AddHttpClient();

builder.Services
	.AddOpenTelemetry()
	.UseAzureMonitor(options =&gt; options.ConnectionString = &#34;InstrumentationKey=[REDACTED] async () =&gt; await Task.Delay(5000));`

In Counter.razor (replace [MyPort] with the port used by the new project):
`private int currentCount;
CancellationTokenSource? _cancellationTokenSource;

[Inject]
HttpClient HttpClient { get =&gt; field ?? throw new Exception(&#34;Property HttpClient is not initialized&#34;); set; }

private async Task IncrementCount()
{
    if (_cancellationTokenSource != null)
        await _cancellationTokenSource.CancelAsync();
    _cancellationTokenSource = new CancellationTokenSource();

   await this.HttpClient.GetAsync(&#34;http://localhost:[MyPort]/test&#34;, _cancellationTokenSource.Token);

   // await Task.Delay(5000, _cancellationTokenSource.Token);

    _cancellationTokenSource.Dispose();
    _cancellationTokenSource = null;

    currentCount++;
}`

### Environment

